    // If current string `s` has `k` ones.
    // `P(s) = k % 2`.
    // If we append `P(s)`:
    //   If `P(s) = 0`: `s` has even `k` ones. Append '0'. New string `s'` has `k` ones. `P(s') = 0`.
    //   If `P(s) = 1`: `s` has odd `k` ones. Append '1'. New string `s'` has `k+1` ones. `P(s') = 0`.
    // So, after one append operation, the parity of the string *always becomes 0*.
    //
    // This means if we want to reach string `b` with parity `P(b)`:
    // 1. If `P(b) = 0`: We can always achieve this. We can append characters until `a` is long enough,
    //    and after each append, the parity becomes 0. So we can always make `a` have parity 0.
