        // The total coins Chanek gets is 1 + (N-1 - solve_opponent_perspective(N-1)).
        // This is not quite right. The problem asks for Chanek's total coins.
        // If Chanek takes 1, he gets 1 coin. Remaining N-1 coins.
        // Now it's opponent's turn with N-1 coins.
        // The opponent will try to maximize their own coins from N-1.
        // Let C(k) be Chanek's optimal coins if starting with k.
        // Let O(k) be opponent's optimal coins if starting with k.
        // If N is odd, Chanek takes 1. Chanek gets 1. Remaining N-1.
        // Now opponent plays on N-1. Opponent gets C(N-1) from N-1.
        // Chanek gets 1 + (N-1 - C(N-1)).
        // This is a recursive definition.
        // Let's re-evaluate the strategy.
        // If N is odd, Chanek takes 1. N becomes N-1 (even).
        // Now it's opponent's turn with N-1.
        // Opponent can take 1 or (N-1)/2.
        // If opponent takes 1, N becomes N-2.
        // If opponent takes (N-1)/2, N becomes (N-1)/2.
        // This is getting complicated. Let's use the observation from the thought process.
