            // Combining these, `p[current_p_idx]` must be in `[x-T, x+T]` for some `x` in `[h[current_h_idx] - T, h[current_h_idx] + T]`.
            // This means the interval `[p[current_p_idx] - T, p[current_p_idx] + T]` must intersect with `[h[current_h_idx] - T, h[current_h_idx] + T]`.
            // This is equivalent to `max(p[current_p_idx] - T, h[current_h_idx] - T) <= min(p[current_p_idx] + T, h[current_h_idx] + T)`.
            // Which simplifies to `abs(p[current_p_idx] - h[current_h_idx]) <= 2 * T`.

            // So, for each `p[current_p_idx]`, we need to find an available head `h[current_h_idx]` such that `abs(p[current_p_idx] - h[current_h_idx]) <= 2 * T`.
            // If we find such a head, we use it. Which one?
            // To cover `p[current_p_idx]` and subsequent points, we should pick the head that can cover `p[current_p_idx]` and extends furthest to the right.
            // If `h[current_h_idx]` is used, it can cover `[h[current_h_idx] - T, h[current_h_idx] + T]` if it stays put.
            // Or it can move to `x` and cover `[x-T, x+T]`.
            // The rightmost point it can cover is `h[current_h_idx] + T + T = h[current_h_idx] + 2T` (by moving to `h[current_h_idx] + T`).
            // The leftmost point it can cover is `h[current_h_idx] - T - T = h[current_h_idx] - 2T` (by moving to `h[current_h_idx] - T`).
            // So, a head `h_i` can cover any point `y` in `[h_i - 2T, h_i + 2T]`.
            // If it covers `y`, it can be moved to `y` (cost `abs(h_i - y) <= 2T`).
            // If it moves to `y`, it covers `[y-T, y+T]`.
            // So, if we use `h_i` to cover `p_j`, we should move it to `x` such that `p_j` is in `[x-T, x+T]` and `x+T` is maximized.
            // This means `x = p_j + T`. But `x` must be reachable from `h_i` in `T` time.
            // So `abs(h_i - (p_j + T)) <= T`.
            // This means `h_i` must be in `[p_j, p_j + 2T]`.
            // If `h_i` is in this range, it can cover `p_j` and extend its reach to `p_j + 2T`.
            // If `h_i` is to the left of `p_j`, say `h_i < p_j`, then it can move right to `h_i + T`.
            // This covers `[h_i, h_i + 2T]`.
            // If `h_i` is to the right of `p_j + 2T`, say `h_i > p_j + 2T`, then it can move left to `h_i - T`.
            // This covers `[h_i - 2T, h_i]`.

            // The problem is simpler:
            // We have `n` heads. Each head `h_i` can be moved to any `x` such that `abs(h_i - x) <= T`.
            // Once at `x`, it covers `[x-T, x+T]`.
            // So, `h_i` can cover any point `p_j` if there exists an `x` such that `abs(h_i - x) <= T` AND `abs(p_j - x) <= T`.
            // This is equivalent to `abs(h_i - p_j) <= 2 * T`.
            // If `abs(h_i - p_j) <= 2 * T`, then `h_i` can cover `p_j`.
            // If `h_i` covers `p_j`, it can be moved to `x = p_j`. Then it covers `[p_j - T, p_j + T]`.
            // The cost is `abs(h_i - p_j)`. This cost must be `<= T`.
            // This is the initial filtering.

            // The problem is that a head can move to `x` and cover `[x-T, x+T]`.
            // The total time is `T`.
            // So, `abs(h_i - x) <= T`.
            // We need to cover all `p_j`.
            // Let `p_idx` be the index of the leftmost point not yet covered.
            // We need to use a head `h_k` to cover `p[p_idx]`.
            // Which `h_k` should we use?
            // We should use the leftmost available `h_k` such that it can cover `p[p_idx]` and extend its coverage as far right as possible.
            // If `h_k` covers `p[p_idx]`, it must move to some `x` such that `abs(h_k - x) <= T` and `p[p_idx]` is in `[x-T, x+T]`.
            // To maximize `x+T`, we should maximize `x`.
            // The maximum `x` is `h_k + T`. This covers `[h_k, h_k + 2T]`.
            // The minimum `x` is `h_k - T`. This covers `[h_k - 2T, h_k]`.
            // So, `h_k` can cover any point in `[h_k - 2T, h_k + 2T]`.
            // If `h_k` covers `p[p_idx]`, it must be that `h_k - 2T <= p[p_idx] <= h_k + 2T`.
            // Or `p[p_idx] - 2T <= h_k <= p[p_idx] + 2T`.

            // Let's use the greedy strategy:
            // `p_ptr` is the index of the leftmost point that still needs to be covered.
            // `h_ptr` is the index of the next head we can use.
            // While `p_ptr < m`:
            //   If `h_ptr == n`, we ran out of heads, so return false.
            //   We need to cover `p[p_ptr]`.
            //   Find the first head `h[h_ptr]` (or later) that can cover `p[p_ptr]`.
            //   A head `h_i` can cover `p[p_ptr]` if `h_i` can reach some `x` such that `p[p_ptr]` is in `[x-T, x+T]`.
            //   This means `h_i` must be in `[p[p_ptr] - T, p[p_ptr] + T]` if it stays put.
